text: It seems to me a lot of people here are missing the point. Nobody is trying to glorify colonialism, slavery, racism, etc. This is a movie about friendship. If anything, the white people (Queen Victoria's court/household/family/the British aristocracy) are the "villains" here. They are the ones that are clearly portrayed as scheming, jealous, petty, and cruel. But let's not lose sight of the fact that this is a STORY.  Anyone that watches a movie, reads a book, etc. and just automatically takes it to be true is an idiot. It's a given that this story is BASED on a true story, is told from mainly one POV, and clearly doesn't have the capacity to be accurate in every way. You want to know what really happened between England and India, then please check out multiple, reliable NON-FICTION sources. It's true that it's a somewhat light-hearted story set in a time/place that had a lot of terrible things going on (it's also true that the movie is no particular masterpiece). But it would also be short-sighted to assume that everything about those circumstances was evil. Lighten up and don't add to the atrocity by sowing even more resentment and hate!
